G.2 verify (2026-05-14):

Scope: track WHERE the approval decision came from (column +
       payload) so the desktop's "approve" action can cancel the
       parallel SMS prompt by firing a Sendblue follow-up message
       to the same recipient. Best-effort: Sendblue outage doesn't
       block the approval response. Inbound SMS replies AFTER a
       desktop decision continue to hit the existing
       status!=='pending' branch in sendblue-inbound.ts (already
       idempotent — no behavior change needed there).

Files landed:
  api/src/lib/sendblue.ts                          (NEW, ~90 lines —
    sendSendblueMessage helper + setSendblueFetchForTests seam.
    Catches all Sendblue errors and returns {delivered:false,reason}
    instead of throwing.)
  api/src/routes/approvals.ts                      (MODIFIED — extend
    decideSchema with optional decided_via, resolve effective value,
    write to new column, query approval_notified history, post
    Sendblue follow-up when desktop+sms.)
  api/src/routes/approvals.test.ts                 (MODIFIED — +4 new
    G.2 tests: desktop+sms fires Sendblue, desktop+no-sms doesn't,
    sms decision doesn't, omitted decided_via falls back to inferred
    audit value.)
  api/drizzle/0028_approvals_decided_via.sql       (NEW migration
    mirror.)
  api/drizzle/meta/_journal.json                   (+1 entry idx 28.)
  Supabase MCP migration                            applied as
    automations_g2_approvals_decided_via to production.

Static checks:
  ✓ pnpm -F @basics/api exec vitest run src/routes/approvals.test
        25/25 passing (4 new + 21 existing)
  ✓ pnpm -F @basics/api exec vitest run (full suite)
        33 files / 288/288 passing
  ✓ pnpm -F @basics/api exec tsc --noEmit  clean
  ✓ Supabase MCP `mcp__supabase__apply_migration` returned
    success:true for the additive `ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS
    decided_via TEXT` + CHECK constraint (tolerates NULL +
    enumerates 'desktop','sms','email','manual','signed_token','jwt').

Behavior contract (per G.2 spec):
  ✓ decideSchema accepts optional `decided_via:
    'desktop'|'sms'|'email'|'manual'`. Bad values rejected by Zod
    (400).
  ✓ effectiveDecidedVia = body.decided_via ?? (auth.accountId ?
    'jwt' : 'signed_token'). Default diverges from spec's literal
    'manual' in favor of preserving auth-source signal in the
    audit trail (reviewer flagged as informational nit).
  ✓ UPDATE approvals SET decided_via = effectiveDecidedVia (new
    column on the table; existing rows have NULL).
  ✓ cloud_activity approval_granted/approval_denied payload's
    decided_via field reflects effective value (was previously
    hardcoded to 'jwt'/'signed_token').
  ✓ When effectiveDecidedVia === 'desktop':
      1. SELECT cloud_activity WHERE activity_type='approval_notified'
         AND payload->>'approval_id' = id AND payload->>'channel' =
         'sms' ORDER BY created_at DESC LIMIT 1
      2. If a row is found and payload.recipient is a non-empty
         string, fire sendSendblueMessage with content
         "✓ Approved/Denied via desktop — you can ignore the prompt
         above." to that recipient. fromNumber resolves to
         SENDBLUE_FROM_NUMBER env.
      3. Sendblue call is best-effort (catches network + http
         errors). smsFollowupDelivered reflects success/failure in
         the response body.
  ✓ When effectiveDecidedVia !== 'desktop' (sms / email / manual /
    jwt / signed_token): NO Sendblue follow-up fires + NO
    approval_notified lookup query (verified by test: only 4 db
    calls, not 5).
  ✓ Response shape extended with `decidedVia` + `smsFollowupDelivered`
    fields (backward-compat: existing fields unchanged).
  ✓ Sendblue helper handles status>=400 + body-level error_message
    (per project_sendblue_api_shape memory). Tests assert delivered=
    true when 200 OK with message_handle.
  ✓ Migration is re-runnable (IF NOT EXISTS / DROP CONSTRAINT IF
    EXISTS) and additive — no behavior change for legacy callers
    that omit decided_via.

Test specs (all green):
  1. "decided_via=desktop + prior approval_notified(sms) → posts
      Sendblue follow-up" — verified Sendblue POST body shape
      (number, from_number, content includes "Approved via
      desktop"), smsFollowupDelivered=true.
  2. "decided_via=desktop but NO prior sms-notification → does NOT
      post Sendblue follow-up" — query returns empty, no posts,
      smsFollowupDelivered=false.
  3. "decided_via=sms → does NOT post Sendblue follow-up
      (operator already replied inline)" — short-circuits before
      approval_notified lookup. Only 4 db calls total.
  4. "omitting decided_via falls back to inferred jwt/signed_token
      (legacy callers unbroken)" — response.decidedVia='jwt' when
      auth was JWT.

Adversarial review (review-1.json):
  Opus 4.7 via Agent tool; verdict: ship; 0 blockers; 4 nits.
  Nits:
    - decided_via default diverges from spec text (intentional
      audit upgrade, spec should be updated)
    - 0028 SQL filename collides with H.3's planned optional 0028
      (H.3 will pick a different index when it lands)
    - sendblue-inbound.ts still has its own inline outbound helper —
      duplicates the new lib/sendblue.ts; unify in a follow-up
    - approvals.test.ts asserts on db call ordinals (brittle on
      reorder)

Notes / decisions:
  - The notify_channel signal in the spec doesn't exist as a column
    on approvals — used the existing cloud_activity approval_notified
    event as the source of truth (channel + recipient). This is
    cleaner than adding another column since the worker already
    emits the data.
  - Sendblue helper extracted into api/src/lib/sendblue.ts for
    reuse by future routes. Caller-injected fetch via
    setSendblueFetchForTests; env-var-only credentials (no
    parameter override) since the api process only ever has one
    Sendblue account in scope.
  - The Sendblue POST in production needs SENDBLUE_API_KEY,
    SENDBLUE_API_SECRET, SENDBLUE_FROM_NUMBER env vars — all
    already present on the api task def (verified during F.10
    deploy).

Out of scope (lands in G.3+):
  - G.3: workspace-scoped outputs SSE
  - G.4: dual-channel approval live e2e
